import json

data = [
    {
        "index": "103.0",
        "refashioned": "Having addressed creation and the diversity of things, we turn to divine governance: first in general terms, then its specific effects. Eight questions frame the discussion: Does the world have a governor? What is the goal of that governance? Is there one governor or many? What are the effects of governance? Is everything subject to it? Does God govern everything directly? Can anything fall outside divine governance? Can anything resist it?"
    },
    {
        "index": "103.1",
        "refashioned": "The world is governed. The objection that natural things lack knowledge of their purpose, and therefore cannot be governed, misunderstands governance. An arrow does not know its target, yet its flight toward it proves an archer aimed it. The consistent patterns we observe in nature -- things regularly achieving beneficial outcomes -- are evidence of direction, not accident. A well-ordered house implies someone ordered it.\n\nThis follows also from God's goodness. If God brought things into existence, it would be inconsistent with supreme goodness to abandon them without guiding them toward their fulfillment. A thing's ultimate perfection lies in reaching its proper end. So the same goodness that caused creation also sustains governance.\n\nEven things that seem stable still require governance. Created from nothing, they would collapse back into nothing without sustaining direction. And the natural necessity that determines how things behave is itself a kind of divine imprint -- like the archer's force impressed on the arrow. Natural law does not replace governance; it is governance operating through the natures of things."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.2",
        "refashioned": "The ultimate goal of the world's governance lies outside the world itself. The reasoning is straightforward: the cause of everything is external to the universe -- God -- and the end of a thing corresponds to its beginning. Since nothing within creation is good by its own essence but only by participation in goodness, the ultimate good toward which everything is directed must be the Universal Good that is good in itself: God.\n\nThis does not mean creatures gain nothing internally. A thing can attain an external good by possessing or participating in it, not only by containing it. The internal order of the universe is real and valuable, but it is not the final end. It is itself ordered to something beyond, the way the order of an army exists for the sake of the general's objective, not for its own sake."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.3",
        "refashioned": "The world must be governed by one. Since the end of governance is the supreme good, governance must be of the highest quality. And the best governance is governance by one.\n\nThe reason: governance means directing things toward their end, and that end is some form of good. But goodness and unity are inseparable -- everything that desires good also desires unity, because a thing exists only insofar as it is one. Things resist division; dissolution comes from internal failure. So the goal of any ruler over a multitude is unity and peace, and one ruler is better suited to produce unity than many acting in coordination, since the many must first be united among themselves before they can unify anything else.\n\nThe diversity of movements and operations in the world does not indicate multiple governors. That diversity belongs to the things governed, not the governing principle. And when contraries oppose each other in their immediate effects, they still serve one overarching order in the universe."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.4",
        "refashioned": "Divine governance produces three levels of effect. At the most fundamental level, there is one effect: everything becomes like the supreme good through participation. At a structural level, there are two effects: God preserves things in their existing goodness, and God moves things toward greater good. The creature becomes like God both by being good and by causing goodness in others. At the level of individual creatures, the effects are without number, since every particular thing governed represents a distinct instance of divine direction."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.5a",
        "refashioned": "Everything without exception is subject to divine governance. The same reason God is the cause of all being is the reason He governs all being. God is not the cause of one particular kind of existence but of existence universally. Therefore nothing can exist outside His governance, just as nothing can exist without being created by Him.\n\nThis also follows from the nature of governance's end. God's governance aims at the divine goodness, and since everything is ordered to divine goodness as its ultimate end, nothing can escape that ordering.\n\nThe opinion that God does not govern corruptible things, individual things, or human affairs is therefore mistaken."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.5b",
        "refashioned": "The fact that chance events occur in the natural world does not disprove divine governance -- it actually confirms it. Chance means that something happens outside the order of a particular cause, and this is only possible if those causes are themselves governed by something higher. Without governance, nothing would tend toward any definite outcome, and without definite outcomes, chance (which is deviation from expected outcomes) could not exist.\n\nAs for the objection that God has no care for irrational creatures: the point is not that they fall outside governance entirely, but that they are governed differently than rational creatures. God governs rational beings both by moving them internally and by addressing them through commands, rewards, and consequences. Irrational creatures are governed through their natures alone, without moral address.\n\nAnd the rational creature's ability to govern itself through intellect and will does not exempt it from divine governance. Both intellect and will themselves require perfecting by the divine intellect and will. Self-governance operates beneath, not outside, God's governance."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.6",
        "refashioned": "God governs all things directly in design but not in execution. The distinction matters.\n\nRegarding the plan of governance -- providence itself -- God governs every detail immediately. The best governor is not the one who handles only broad strokes but the one who knows every particular. A great physician does not just know general medical principles; she attends to the specifics of each patient.\n\nRegarding execution, however, God governs some things through intermediaries. This is not a deficiency but a mark of superior governance. A thing's perfection is greater when it is not only good in itself but also a cause of goodness in others. So God delegates causal roles to creatures, the way a master teacher not only teaches students but equips them to teach others.\n\nPlato was wrong to divide providence itself among multiple levels of deity. An earthly king's use of ministers does not indicate weakness -- it magnifies the reach of royal authority. Similarly, God's use of secondary causes enhances rather than diminishes the order of creation."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.7",
        "refashioned": "Nothing can happen outside the order of divine governance taken as a whole, though things can happen outside the order of any particular cause within it.\n\nThe principle: every exception to a particular cause is itself caused by something else, and that something else is itself reducible to the universal first cause. If indigestion occurs despite the nutritive power, it is because of the coarseness of the food, which itself has a cause, and so on back to God. Since God is the universal cause of all being -- not just one type -- nothing can escape the total order.\n\nThis does not eliminate evil, chance, or contingency. Evil exists because things deviate from particular goods, but anything that entirely escaped divine order would cease to exist altogether. Chance is real relative to particular causes but does not exist relative to the universal cause. And contingent events are contingent relative to their immediate causes, which can fail, but every such failure itself falls within the broader divine order."
    },
    {
        "index": "103.8",
        "refashioned": "Nothing can truly resist the order of divine governance, though things can resist particular goods within it.\n\nTwo reasons establish this. First, divine governance is entirely directed toward good, and everything by nature seeks good -- no agent acts intending evil as such. Second, every natural or voluntary inclination is an impression from the first mover, like an arrow's trajectory is an impression from the archer. Every agent, whether acting by nature or by free choice, ultimately reaches its divinely appointed end.\n\nWhen people act \"against God,\" they resist some particular good that belongs to their nature or situation, not the total order of providence. A sinner pursues a genuine good (pleasure, power, security) but in a disordered way. The resistance is real at the level of particular goods, which is why punishment is just. But the overall order of divine governance absorbs even rebellion into its total design."
    },
    {
        "index": "104.0",
        "refashioned": "We now examine the specific effects of divine governance through four questions: Do creatures need God to sustain their existence? Does God preserve them directly? Can God reduce anything to nothingness? Does anything actually get annihilated?"
    },
    {
        "index": "104.1a",
        "refashioned": "Do creatures need God to keep them in existence, or can they persist on their own once created?\n\nSeveral objections suggest they can. Some beings -- like angels or celestial bodies -- seem by nature incapable of ceasing to exist. A builder's house stands after the builder leaves, so surely God's creations can persist after the act of creation. And nothing violent happens without an active cause, yet no active cause can corrupt a spiritual substance.\n\nBut these objections misunderstand the relationship between creature and Creator."
    },
    {
        "index": "104.1b",
        "refashioned": "Both reason and faith require us to say that creatures are kept in being by God continuously.\n\nThe key distinction: a cause can relate to its effect in two ways. Some causes produce the becoming of a thing but not its ongoing being. A builder causes a house to come into existence, but the house's continued existence depends on the nature of its materials, not on the builder. Once built, the house stands on its own because the builder did not cause the form of stone and wood as such -- he only arranged pre-existing materials.\n\nBut when a cause is responsible not just for a thing's becoming but for its very being -- for the form itself, not merely for its arrangement in matter -- then the effect cannot persist without the cause's ongoing action. The analogy: air is lit up by the sun. The sun does not merely start the light and leave; the air has no capacity to hold light on its own. The moment the sun stops acting, the air goes dark. Hot water, by contrast, retains heat after the fire is removed, because water can receive heat as its own quality.\n\nEvery creature relates to God as the air relates to the sun. God alone exists by His own essence -- His essence is His existence. Every creature has existence only by participation, borrowed from God's ongoing creative act. Withdraw that act for a single moment, and the creature would collapse into nothing. God's preservation of things is not a separate act from creation; it is the continuation of the same act by which existence is given."
    },
    {
        "index": "104.1c",
        "refashioned": "The fact that some creatures seem incapable of corruption does not mean they are self-sustaining. Their potentiality for non-being lies not in their own nature but in God, who could withdraw His sustaining influence. God cannot make a creature that does not need Him, because the creature's dependence on God for being is not a feature that could be removed -- it is constitutive of what it means to be a creature rather than God. And God's preservation is not an additional action that adds something new to the creature; it is the continuous pouring-out of existence, the same act that first gave being."
    },
    {
        "index": "104.2",
        "refashioned": "God does not preserve every creature immediately. He preserves some things through other things.\n\nThis works in two ways. First, indirectly: certain creatures prevent other creatures from being corrupted, the way salt preserves meat. Second, directly: when an effect depends on a chain of causes, each intermediate cause plays a role in sustaining the effect. The first cause remains the primary preserver, but the middle causes genuinely contribute to preservation in a secondary way.\n\nGod created all things directly but established an order of dependence among them in the act of creation itself. Some creatures depend on other creatures for their continued existence, though all ultimately depend on God as the principal sustaining cause. This layered preservation is not a deficiency in God's power but the deliberate structure of a creation in which creatures participate in sustaining one another."
    },
    {
        "index": "104.3",
        "refashioned": "God can annihilate anything. Since God created freely -- not out of natural necessity -- He is equally free to stop sustaining a creature in existence. God's preservation of things is a continuous act, like the sun's continuous illumination of the air. Just as He was free not to create in the first place, He is free to withdraw His sustaining action, at which point the creature would simply cease to be.\n\nThis does not make God a direct cause of non-existence. Nothing directly causes non-being, since causation presupposes being. Rather, annihilation would be an indirect result: God ceasing to act, rather than God acting to destroy. Nor does this contradict God's goodness, since His goodness does not depend on creatures and was not compelled to produce them."
    },
    {
        "index": "104.4",
        "refashioned": "In practice, God does not annihilate anything. While He has the power to do so, nothing in the natural order of things tends toward annihilation, and miracles serve the manifestation of grace rather than destruction.\n\nNature shows no tendency toward annihilation. Matter persists through all transformations -- forms come and go, but the underlying substrate endures. Even when forms and qualities cease to exist in one thing, they do not become nothing; the matter takes on new forms. And spiritual substances, which have no matter, are by nature incorruptible.\n\nFrom the side of grace, annihilation would serve no purpose. The manifestation of divine power and goodness is better demonstrated by preserving things in existence than by reducing them to nothing. Scripture confirms this: \"All the works that God has made continue forever.\""
    },
    {
        "index": "105.0",
        "refashioned": "We now consider how God acts on creatures -- not just sustaining them in existence but actively changing and moving them. Eight questions: Does God directly move the created intellect? Can God move the will? Does God work in every agent? Can God do anything outside the natural order? What are miracles? Why are there different grades of miracle? Can God perform miracles through creatures? And: can God do anything beyond what He has established as the natural order?"
    },
    {
        "index": "105.1",
        "refashioned": "God can directly illuminate the created intellect. The intellect is a power of the soul, and like all created powers, it exists as potentiality that requires activation. Just as the senses need sensible objects and a medium (like light for sight), the intellect needs both intelligible content and intellectual light to understand.\n\nA created intellect can fail to grasp something for two reasons: lack of the relevant intellectual light, or lack of the intelligible content itself. God can supply both. He can strengthen the intellect's natural light -- granting greater capacity to understand -- and He can impress intelligible forms directly, providing content the intellect could not derive from sense experience alone.\n\nGod does not thereby violate the intellect's nature. He acts as the source of all intellectual light, supplementing what the natural light cannot reach on its own. Prophetic knowledge is an example: the prophet receives both enhanced light and new intelligible content directly from God."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.2a",
        "refashioned": "Can God move the human will? Yes -- and only God can move the will directly from within, because the will's proper object is the universal good, and only the universal good itself (God) is proportionate to that object.\n\nAny created good can present itself as desirable under some aspect, but no created good can necessitate the will, because the will is oriented toward goodness as such. Only what perfectly fulfills that orientation can move the will from within as a sufficient cause. External objects and other agents can present goods to the will, but they move it only indirectly -- by presenting something attractive. God alone moves the will as an interior principle, inclining it from within without destroying its freedom."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.2b",
        "refashioned": "Being moved by God does not destroy freedom. The will is by nature a voluntary, self-moving power, and God moves it in accordance with its nature -- not by force but by interior inclination. Just as God moves natural things according to their natures (heavy things downward, light things upward) without making their motion violent, so He moves the will according to its nature as a free power, without making its motion involuntary.\n\nGod is the universal cause who works through the particular natures of things. He does not override the will any more than He overrides gravity. He is the reason the will can act at all, and His motion is what makes voluntary action possible rather than what threatens it."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.3",
        "refashioned": "God works in every agent that operates. Not alongside the agent as a separate cause, but as the foundational cause that makes the agent's own causality possible.\n\nThis happens in three ways. First, God gives and sustains the forms and powers by which agents act. A thing acts through its form, and that form exists only because God gives and maintains it. Second, God sustains the forms and powers in their activity -- they would lose their operative capacity the moment God withdrew His sustaining influence, just as a thing loses existence when God ceases to uphold it. Third, God applies every agent to its action. No secondary cause moves from potency to act except by being moved by a prior cause, and this chain leads ultimately to God as the first mover.\n\nSo God is not merely the originator who set things in motion and stepped back. He is actively involved in every operation: giving the power, maintaining the power, and applying the power to its act. The secondary cause genuinely acts -- it is not an illusion -- but it acts by a power that derives from and depends on God at every moment."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.4",
        "refashioned": "God can produce effects in the natural world without using natural causes -- that is, He can act outside the established natural order. This follows from two considerations.\n\nFirst, the natural order is not imposed on God; it flows from God. Just as someone who establishes a system can also operate outside that system when there is reason to, God who established nature can act beyond it. Second, the natural order reflects the current arrangement of created causes, but God's power is not limited to what those causes can produce. He can produce effects that no natural cause could produce (like creating something from nothing), effects that natural causes could produce but in a different order or manner, and effects in matter that is not naturally disposed to receive them.\n\nThis does not mean God acts arbitrarily or contradicts Himself. Nature's order reflects divine wisdom, and acts outside that order also reflect divine wisdom -- serving purposes (like the manifestation of grace) that the regular order alone cannot accomplish."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.5a",
        "refashioned": "When God acts outside the natural order in a way that is observable, we call it a miracle. The word itself comes from wonder -- what provokes astonishment because its cause is hidden. A miracle in the strict sense is something that surpasses the entire order of created nature, not just the capacity of one particular natural cause."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.5b",
        "refashioned": "Miracles are not all of the same rank. They differ in three ways, corresponding to three degrees of exceeding natural power.\n\nThe highest miracles involve things that nature can never do under any circumstances -- like two bodies occupying the same space, or the sun reversing its course, or a human body being glorified. These exceed nature absolutely.\n\nThe second rank involves things nature can do but not in this particular subject. Nature can produce life, but not life in a dead body. Nature can produce sight, but not in a person born blind. The effect itself is natural; its occurrence in this subject is not.\n\nThe third rank involves things nature could produce in this subject but not in this way -- healing that nature could eventually accomplish but that happens instantaneously, or rain that comes without any natural meteorological cause.\n\nWithin each rank, miracles vary further according to how far they surpass the natural power involved."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.5c",
        "refashioned": "Strictly speaking, only God can work miracles, because miracles by definition exceed the entire order of created nature, and only God acts above that order. Created agents -- even angels -- operate within the order of creation, not above it."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.6",
        "refashioned": "Can God do things beyond the natural order He has established? Absolutely. The natural order of things was established by God freely, not out of necessity. And there are purposes that transcend what the natural order alone can display -- specifically, the manifestation of grace and divine power. Miracles serve these purposes.\n\nThis does not mean God acts against nature in the sense of contradicting it. Rather, God acts above nature. The natural order is embedded within a larger divine order, and when God acts miraculously, He is not breaking His own system -- He is operating at a level that the natural system was always subordinate to.\n\nNor does this generate disorder. Every miracle, however surprising from the perspective of natural causes, is perfectly orderly from the perspective of divine wisdom. Things only seem irregular when judged by the standard of a particular cause; judged by the universal cause, everything is ordered."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.7",
        "refashioned": "Can God do anything beyond what He has in fact ordained? Yes. God's power is not limited to what He has actually chosen to do. His wisdom and power exceed the created order, which represents one possible arrangement among many that divine wisdom could have established.\n\nBut God cannot do anything that involves a logical contradiction -- not because of a limitation in power, but because contradictions are not real possibilities. The phrase \"God cannot make a square circle\" does not describe a limit on God; it describes the fact that \"square circle\" is not a coherent thing to make. Setting aside contradictions, God's power extends beyond any created order.\n\nThis also means that God is not bound to maintain the current natural order. He freely established it and could freely establish a different one. What He does is always consistent with His wisdom, but His wisdom is not constrained to a single possible expression."
    },
    {
        "index": "105.8",
        "refashioned": "God never acts against His own wisdom and goodness, even when He acts outside the natural order. What appears contrary to nature from a limited perspective is not contrary to the divine order. Just as a household servant might find the master's instructions puzzling without seeing the larger plan, what seems unusual relative to a particular natural cause makes perfect sense relative to the universal cause.\n\nGod does not change His mind or correct course. His eternal plan encompasses both the natural order and every exception to it. Miracles are not afterthoughts or patches; they are part of the original design, serving purposes that the routine order of nature alone could not fulfill."
    },
    {
        "index": "106.0",
        "refashioned": "We now turn to how creatures influence one another -- beginning with purely spiritual creatures (angels), then physical bodies, then human beings (who are both). Regarding angels, three topics arise: how angels act on other angels, how angels act on physical nature, and how angels act on human beings. The first of these covers enlightenment and speech among angels, plus the coordination of both good and bad angels. On enlightenment specifically, four questions: Can one angel enlighten another? Can one angel move another's will? Can a lower angel enlighten a higher one? Does a higher angel share everything it knows with a lower one?"
    },
    {
        "index": "106.1a",
        "refashioned": "One angel can enlighten another. The objection that angels in beatitude have no need for teaching from one another mistakes the nature of angelic enlightenment. In the state of glory, no one needs external instruction about God Himself -- all see God directly. But understanding how divine truth unfolds in its effects and applications admits of degrees, and here higher angels can clarify for lower ones what the lower ones grasp only in more general or obscure terms.\n\nAngelic enlightenment is not the transfer of natural light, grace, or glory -- those come from God alone. Rather, one angel strengthens another's capacity to grasp a truth, the way a teacher does not give a student new eyes but helps the student see what was there to be seen."
    },
    {
        "index": "106.1b",
        "refashioned": "The mechanism of angelic enlightenment works through proportioning truth to the receiver's capacity. Higher angels grasp truths in more unified, universal forms. Lower angels need those truths broken down into more specific, particular forms to understand them. The higher angel \"enlightens\" the lower by presenting truth in a form proportioned to the lower angel's intellect -- not dumbing it down, but structuring it so the lesser intellect can receive it.\n\nThis is analogous to how a brilliant theorist translates an insight for someone who cannot yet grasp the full abstraction. The content is the same; the mode of presentation changes to match the receiver."
    },
    {
        "index": "106.2",
        "refashioned": "One angel cannot directly move another angel's will. The will can only be moved from within by its proper object -- the universal good -- and only God is that. An angel can present something desirable to another angel's intellect, which may indirectly influence the other's will by giving it something new to consider. But no creature can reach into another's will and move it as an interior cause.\n\nAngels can also influence each other by persuasion and by manifesting goods that attract the will. But the actual determination of the will -- the interior act of choosing -- remains inviolable to any external created agent. Only God moves the will from within, because only God is proportionate to the will's deepest object."
    },
    {
        "index": "106.3",
        "refashioned": "A lower angel cannot enlighten a higher one. Enlightenment moves from greater understanding to lesser, not the reverse. While a lower angel can speak to a higher one -- communicating its own thoughts -- this is not enlightenment in the proper sense, because enlightenment requires the one illuminating to have a more universal and powerful grasp of the truth than the one being illuminated.\n\nIn human experience, a student can inform a teacher of a particular fact, but this is not the same as illumination. Illumination flows from the stronger intellect to the weaker, making the weaker capable of grasping what it could not grasp on its own."
    },
    {
        "index": "106.4",
        "refashioned": "A higher angel does not communicate everything it knows to a lower angel. It communicates truths proportioned to the lower angel's capacity, which means the content is adapted and particularized. The higher angel grasps things in a more universal mode that exceeds what the lower angel can receive, so what gets transmitted is always a partial and accommodated version of what the higher angel knows.\n\nThis is not stinginess but structural necessity. A vessel can only receive what its shape allows. The knowledge that defines the higher angel's rank remains proper to that rank and cannot simply be poured whole into a lower intellect."
    },
    {
        "index": "107.0",
        "refashioned": "Having discussed enlightenment among angels, we now consider angelic speech -- how angels communicate their thoughts to one another. Five questions: How does one angel speak to another? Can a lower angel speak to a higher one? Does an angel speak to God? Does spatial distance affect angelic communication? Can one angel's speech be known to all others, or can it be private?"
    },
    {
        "index": "107.1a",
        "refashioned": "Angels do speak to one another, though not through sound or language in any physical sense. An angel's interior concept is naturally hidden from other angels -- knowing another's essence does not automatically mean knowing their current thoughts. When one angel wills to make its thought known to another, that constitutes speech.\n\nAngelic speech is simply the voluntary directing of one's mental content toward another intellect. The \"word\" is the concept itself, and \"speaking\" is the act of making it available to the other. This requires no medium, no encoding, no physical channel -- only the speaker's will to communicate."
    },
    {
        "index": "107.1b",
        "refashioned": "The mechanism is straightforward: an angel's thought, when voluntarily directed to another, becomes intelligible to that other. The speaker's will functions as the act of disclosure. What is naturally private becomes accessible because the speaker opens it. No sensory apparatus is needed because both parties operate as pure intellects. The content transmitted is the intelligible form of the concept itself."
    },
    {
        "index": "107.2",
        "refashioned": "A lower angel can speak to a higher one. Speech and enlightenment are different acts. Enlightenment flows only downward because it requires the illuminator to have a more powerful grasp of the truth. But speech is simply the voluntary disclosure of one's thought to another, and any angel can do this to any other, regardless of rank. A lower angel may communicate information, requests, or observations to a higher one without this constituting enlightenment."
    },
    {
        "index": "107.3",
        "refashioned": "Angels do speak to God -- not to inform Him, since He already knows everything, but to express themselves. Angelic speech to God takes two forms: consulting the divine will about what to do, and admiring the divine excellence. Both are genuine acts of communication even though God gains no new information from them. Speaking to God is the creature's way of orienting itself toward its source, not a transfer of knowledge."
    },
    {
        "index": "107.4",
        "refashioned": "Spatial distance is irrelevant to angelic speech. Physical distance affects communication only when the medium of communication is physical -- sound waves weaken over distance, for instance. But angelic speech uses no physical medium. It operates through the direct voluntary orientation of one intellect toward another, and this requires no spatial proximity.\n\nHowever, the higher an angel's rank, the more broadly it can communicate, because higher angels have a more universal grasp of truth. A higher angel can address more recipients with richer content, not because of spatial reach, but because of intellectual scope."
    },
    {
        "index": "107.5",
        "refashioned": "Angelic speech can be private. When one angel directs a thought to another, only the intended recipient and God perceive it. Communication requires the speaker's will to disclose to a specific audience. An angel can address one peer without all others overhearing, because the act of disclosure is voluntary and targeted.\n\nGod alone always perceives every angelic thought, whether disclosed or not. But among angels, privacy is the default; communication is a deliberate act of opening."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.0",
        "refashioned": "We now examine the hierarchical ordering of angels -- how they are organized into ranks and functions. Eight questions guide the discussion: Are all angels in one hierarchy? Is there only one order within a hierarchy? Are there multiple angels in one order? Is the distinction of hierarchies and orders based on nature? What are the names and properties of each order? How do the orders relate to one another? Will the current ordering persist after the final judgment? Can human beings be received into angelic orders?"
    },
    {
        "index": "108.1",
        "refashioned": "Not all angels belong to one hierarchy. A hierarchy is a sacred governance, meaning an organized community directed toward God under a single principle of authority. But angels differ in how they receive divine illumination. Some receive it directly from God with maximum clarity and universality; others receive it through intermediaries, in more particular and limited forms.\n\nThis yields three hierarchies based on proximity to the divine source. The highest hierarchy receives illumination directly from God in universal terms. The middle hierarchy receives it through the highest, in terms applicable to general created causes. The lowest hierarchy receives it in terms applicable to particular and immediate things. The analogy: a mayor receives policy directly from the sovereign; department heads get it from the mayor; front-line workers get it from the department heads. Each level understands the same broad purpose but in terms proportioned to its sphere of operation."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.2",
        "refashioned": "Within each hierarchy, there are multiple orders. An order is a group of angels that share the same grade of excellence and function. Since angelic action takes three essential forms -- receiving illumination, understanding it, and carrying it out in subordinate realms -- each hierarchy naturally divides into three orders.\n\nIn the highest hierarchy: the first order (Seraphim) excels in union with God through love; the second (Cherubim) excels in the fullness of knowledge; the third (Thrones) excels in receiving and holding divine judgments. In the middle hierarchy: the first order (Dominations) directs what is to be done; the second (Virtues) provides the power to carry it out; the third (Powers) determines how particular tasks are ordered and executed. In the lowest hierarchy: Principalities preside over nations and large groups; Archangels handle important messages; Angels handle ordinary ministrations to individuals."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.3",
        "refashioned": "There are indeed multiple angels within each order. An order is not a single angel but a collection of angels at the same grade. Since angelic natures differ as species differ -- each angel being its own kind -- the angels within one order share a functional rank while differing from one another in their individual natures.\n\nWithin each order, there are gradations. Some angels are closer to the top of their order, others closer to the bottom. The ordering is not rigid in the sense that every angel is exactly equal to its order-mates, but they share enough in common to be grouped under the same rank and function."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.4",
        "refashioned": "The distinction of hierarchies and orders is based on nature, but not on nature alone. Angels differ naturally in intellectual capacity -- some are more powerful intellects than others, and this natural gradation forms the basis for the hierarchical ordering. But the actual assignment to hierarchies and orders also involves grace, since the angels' rank in glory corresponds to their degree of grace, which itself was proportioned to their natural capacity.\n\nSo the hierarchy reflects both nature and grace, with nature providing the foundation and grace perfecting it. An angel's natural intellectual power determines the range of what it can receive; grace determines the fullness of what it actually receives."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.5a",
        "refashioned": "The traditional names of the angelic orders -- Seraphim, Cherubim, Thrones, Dominations, Virtues, Powers, Principalities, Archangels, and Angels -- describe functions rather than species.\n\nSeraphim means \"the burning ones,\" signifying their supreme ardor in loving God. Cherubim means \"fullness of knowledge,\" signifying their direct and complete vision of divine truth. Thrones signify the seat of divine judgment -- these angels receive and hold God's judicial decisions. Dominations direct and command what is to be done below them. Virtues confer the power to execute great and difficult operations. Powers impose order and prevent disorder in the execution of divine governance. Principalities preside over broad domains. Archangels carry messages of special importance. Angels handle ordinary ministry to individuals."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.5b",
        "refashioned": "The properties assigned to each order follow from their functions.\n\nIn the highest hierarchy, all three orders are characterized by immediate relationship to God. Seraphim relate to God through supreme love and intimacy. Cherubim relate through supreme knowledge. Thrones relate through receiving divine authority and judgment directly.\n\nIn the middle hierarchy, the three orders govern the broad execution of divine plans. Dominations determine what should be done -- they command without being commanded by any other created authority. Virtues provide the strength and excellence to accomplish what is commanded, especially extraordinary operations. Powers maintain order and suppress resistance, ensuring that divine commands are not frustrated.\n\nIn the lowest hierarchy, the orders handle the particular application of governance to specific creatures. Principalities manage large-scale collective governance. Archangels handle communications of special significance. Angels perform the most immediate and individual acts of ministry.\n\nAll of these names describe what the angels do, not what they essentially are. The name \"angel\" (messenger) properly belongs to the function of the lowest order, though it is sometimes used generically for all spiritual beings who serve as intermediaries."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.6a",
        "refashioned": "The relationships between the orders follow the hierarchical structure. The higher orders contain eminently whatever belongs to the lower orders, but not vice versa. So the Seraphim possess knowledge (like the Cherubim) and authority (like the Thrones), but in a higher mode -- through the lens of supreme love. The Cherubim possess authority, but through the lens of knowledge.\n\nThe general principle: whatever a lower order has, the higher order has more fully and in a more unified way. But the lower order has its distinctive gift in a more explicit and specialized form."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.6b",
        "refashioned": "The coordination between orders follows the principle that the higher always illuminates and directs the lower. The Dominations command the Virtues and Powers. The Virtues empower and direct the Powers. Principalities direct the Archangels and Angels.\n\nBut this chain of command is not a series of separate, independent operations. Each level acts as a transparent medium for divine governance, passing along not just instructions but understanding. The higher order does not merely issue commands -- it illuminates the lower order so that the lower understands the reasons behind its tasks.\n\nThis pattern mirrors good organizational design: the best structures are those where each level of management not only directs but educates the levels beneath it, so that everyone acts with understanding rather than blind obedience."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.6c",
        "refashioned": "Scripture sometimes uses order-names loosely. The name \"Seraphim\" appears in Isaiah, \"Cherubim\" throughout the Old Testament, and other names appear in various contexts. Some apparent inconsistencies arise because a higher order can perform the function of a lower order -- a Seraph can deliver a message, which is properly an angelic function, but the Seraph does it in a manner befitting its higher rank. The names describe primary functions, not exclusive functions."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.7",
        "refashioned": "The angelic orders will persist after the final judgment, but their external ministry will change. The ordering itself is based on grace and nature, which do not change. The hierarchy of intellectual power and closeness to God remains eternal.\n\nWhat will change is the specific content of their external activities. Angels currently minister to human beings on earth, guiding them toward salvation. After the final judgment, when human salvation is complete, this particular form of ministry will cease. But the angels will continue in their essential activities of contemplating God, loving Him, and rejoicing in the order of creation. Their internal acts -- knowing and loving -- continue forever."
    },
    {
        "index": "108.8",
        "refashioned": "Human beings can be received into angelic orders. Not by becoming angels in nature, but by receiving through grace a degree of divine illumination and elevation that corresponds to an angelic rank. Some human saints are elevated to the rank of Angels, some to Archangels, and so on up to the highest orders.\n\nThis is possible because the hierarchy is ultimately based on closeness to God through grace and glory, not on the type of substance one is. A human being who receives a degree of grace equivalent to that of a Seraph takes a place among the Seraphim, though remaining human in nature. The ordering principle is glory, not species."
    },
    {
        "index": "109.0",
        "refashioned": "We now consider whether there is order among the fallen angels, parallel to the order among the good angels. Four questions: Is there ranking among demons? Is there authority and obedience among them? Does one demon enlighten another? Are they subject to the authority of good angels?"
    },
    {
        "index": "109.1",
        "refashioned": "There is a real ordering among demons. Their fall did not erase their natural gifts -- demons retain the natural intellectual capacities they had as angels, though they lost grace and glory. Since the angelic hierarchy was grounded partly in nature, the natural rankings persist among the fallen.\n\nDemonic order differs fundamentally from angelic order in its principle. Good angels are ordered by justice and charity under divine governance. Demons are ordered by raw natural superiority, with more powerful demons dominating weaker ones. Their ordering serves not divine goodness but their own corrupted purposes.\n\nDivine providence permits and uses this demonic ordering. God's governance extends even to the fallen, not sanctioning their evil but incorporating their activity into the broader divine plan."
    },
    {
        "index": "109.2",
        "refashioned": "Some demons do exercise authority over others, and obedience of a kind exists among them. But this is not genuine authority in the moral sense -- it is domination based on natural superiority and fear, not on right or justice.\n\nAmong the good angels, obedience flows from love and understanding. Among demons, it flows from the natural compulsion of a weaker intellect to defer to a stronger one, combined with their shared malice. A powerful demon can direct lesser demons toward particular targets or strategies, but this coordination is that of a criminal syndicate, not a legitimate government."
    },
    {
        "index": "109.3",
        "refashioned": "Demons cannot truly enlighten one another. Enlightenment in the proper sense -- making another see truth more clearly and directing it toward God -- requires grace and right orientation, which demons lack. A demon can communicate information to another demon, and a more powerful demon's intellect naturally grasps things that lesser demons cannot, but this is not illumination. It is raw intellectual dominance without any ordering toward truth and goodness.\n\nWhat happens among demons is a parody of angelic enlightenment: the form of intellectual communication without its substance, since the substance requires orientation toward God."
    },
    {
        "index": "109.4",
        "refashioned": "Good angels do exercise authority over demons. Since the good angels remain united to God, through whom all power ultimately operates, they are stronger than any demon. The good angels restrain and direct demonic activity within the bounds that divine providence permits.\n\nThis does not mean every individual good angel is stronger than every individual demon in natural power. Some demons were originally higher-ranking angels than some current good angels. But the good angels act with the authority and power of God, which surpasses all natural power. A police officer may be physically weaker than a criminal but acts with the authority of the state.\n\nDemonic activity in the world is therefore not unchecked chaos. It operates within boundaries set by divine governance and enforced, in part, by the good angels."
    },
    {
        "index": "110.0",
        "refashioned": "We now consider how angels act on the physical world. Four questions: Are physical creatures governed by angels? Do physical things obey angelic will directly? Can angels move physical bodies through space? Can angels -- good or bad -- perform miracles?"
    },
    {
        "index": "110.1a",
        "refashioned": "Physical creatures are governed by angels. The principle is that the less perfect is governed by the more perfect, and intellect governs bodies. Since angels are purely intellectual beings and physical things lack intellect, it follows that angels play a governing role over the material world.\n\nThis does not mean every species of physical thing requires its own dedicated angel. The governing relationship is functional, not one-to-one. Angels govern the broader movements and operations of the physical world according to divine providence."
    },
    {
        "index": "110.1b",
        "refashioned": "The governance of physical things by angels works through the hierarchy of causation. Higher, more universal causes govern lower, more particular ones. Angels, being intellectual, operate at a higher level of causality than physical forces. They direct the broad patterns of physical nature -- not by replacing natural causes but by guiding and coordinating them.\n\nAugustine's principle holds: \"All bodies are ruled by the rational spirit of life.\" This does not eliminate natural causation but situates it within a larger governance structure. Physical laws operate as secondary causes within a system ultimately directed by intelligence -- angelic and divine.\n\nThe different angelic orders are not multiplied to match every species of physical thing. Rather, particular physical effects fall under more universal angelic governance, with one angelic function covering many physical types."
    },
    {
        "index": "110.2a",
        "refashioned": "Physical matter does not obey the mere will of angels as if angels could reshape reality by thought alone. Angels cannot create or annihilate matter, cannot directly produce substantial forms in matter, and cannot instantaneously transform things by sheer will.\n\nAngels can, however, use physical forces to produce physical effects -- applying natural causes to achieve specific outcomes, much as a human craftsman uses natural materials and forces to build. The angel's intellectual power lets it understand and manipulate natural processes with a precision and speed that far exceeds human capability, but it still works through natural causation rather than bypassing it.\n\nThe impression of instantaneous obedience arises from the speed and precision of angelic manipulation of natural causes, not from matter responding directly to angelic will."
    },
    {
        "index": "110.2b",
        "refashioned": "The limitation is important: only God has the power to which matter obeys directly. God can produce forms in matter by pure will because He is the author of matter itself. Angels are creatures working within the created order, and their power, however great, operates through that order rather than above it. What looks like matter obeying angelic will is really angelic mastery of natural processes operating at speeds beyond human perception."
    },
    {
        "index": "110.3",
        "refashioned": "Angels can move physical bodies from place to place. Since angels have power superior to physical forces, and physical forces can produce local motion, angels can certainly do so as well. The angel does not need a physical body of its own to accomplish this -- it moves bodies by applying its power directly, the way a magnet moves iron without physical contact in the ordinary sense.\n\nThe angel's power of local motion is finite, so there are limits to what it can move and how quickly. But within those limits, angels can produce real physical displacement of bodies through space."
    },
    {
        "index": "110.4",
        "refashioned": "Neither good nor bad angels can work miracles in the strict sense. A miracle, properly defined, exceeds the entire order of created nature. Angels, however powerful, are part of created nature and operate within it. They cannot produce effects that surpass the whole natural order -- only God can do that.\n\nAngels can produce effects that astonish us because they exceed the power of the particular natural causes we are familiar with. A demon or angel might manipulate natural forces in ways that seem miraculous to us, but these are not true miracles -- they are extraordinary applications of natural power. The difference matters: what seems supernatural to us may be merely superhuman.\n\nTrue miracles -- creation from nothing, resurrection of the dead, the direct transformation of substances -- belong to God alone. Angels serve as instruments of divine miracles when God acts through them, but in such cases the miracle is God's, not the angel's."
    },
    {
        "index": "111.0",
        "refashioned": "We now consider how angels act specifically on human beings. Four questions: Can an angel illuminate the human intellect? Can an angel change the human will? Can an angel affect human imagination and senses? Can an angel act on human sense perception directly?"
    },
    {
        "index": "111.1",
        "refashioned": "Angels can illuminate the human intellect, but the mode differs from how angels enlighten other angels. Human understanding depends on sensory images -- we think through mental pictures, metaphors, and concrete examples. So when an angel illuminates a human mind, it does not work by directly imprinting abstract forms (as with angel-to-angel communication). Instead, it works through the imagination, presenting sensory images and particular examples that the human intellect can then abstract from.\n\nAdditionally, the angel can strengthen the human intellect's own light, making it more capable of understanding. This is like adjusting the brightness on a screen while also providing better content to display. The angel does both: enriches the imaginative material and enhances the intellectual capacity to process it.\n\nThis is why angelic communication to humans typically comes through visions, dreams, and symbolic imagery rather than as direct intellectual transfers. The medium is adapted to the human mode of knowing."
    },
    {
        "index": "111.2",
        "refashioned": "Angels cannot directly change the human will. Only God can move the will from within, because only God is the universal good that constitutes the will's proper interior object.\n\nAngels can, however, influence the will indirectly in two ways. First, by presenting goods to the intellect -- if an angel illuminates the mind about some truth, the will may be attracted to act on it. Second, by stirring the passions and emotions through the body and imagination. An angel (or demon) can arouse feelings of desire, fear, or joy by affecting the bodily processes that underlie emotions. These passions then incline the will, though they cannot compel it.\n\nThe will remains free. No angel can force a human choice. But angels can create conditions -- intellectual clarity, emotional disposition -- that make certain choices more or less attractive."
    },
    {
        "index": "111.3a",
        "refashioned": "Angels can act on the human imagination and senses. Since imagination depends on bodily organs and processes, and angels have the power to move physical things, they can produce changes in the imaginative faculty by manipulating the underlying physical conditions.\n\nThis works whether the person is awake or asleep. In sleep, the normal sensory inputs are reduced, making the influence of angelic manipulation of internal images more noticeable -- which is why angelic communication often occurs in dreams. But even in waking life, an angel can stir imaginative content by affecting the flow of bodily humors and the activity of the sensory organs.\n\nThe angel does this not by creating images from nothing but by rearranging and activating images already stored in the memory and imagination."
    },
    {
        "index": "111.3b",
        "refashioned": "Demons use the same mechanism but for corrupted purposes. A demon can stir the imagination toward fantasies, obsessions, and distorted perceptions by manipulating the same bodily and sensory processes that good angels use for illumination. The difference lies not in the mechanism but in the intention and orientation of the influence."
    },
    {
        "index": "111.4",
        "refashioned": "Angels can affect the external senses as well. They can produce real sensory phenomena -- visible forms, audible sounds, tangible effects -- by manipulating physical elements. When angels appear visibly, they are not taking on real bodies but arranging physical matter (typically condensed air or similar material) into forms that affect the senses.\n\nAngels can also block sense perception by interposing obstacles between the sense organ and the object -- just as anyone can block sight by placing something between eye and object. What angels cannot do is alter the fundamental relationship between a properly functioning sense and its proper object. If the sense organ is working correctly and the object is properly presented, the sense perceives what is there. Angels work within this framework, not against it."
    },
    {
        "index": "112.0",
        "refashioned": "We consider the mission of angels -- their being sent by God to perform tasks in the world. Four questions: Are angels sent on missions? Are all angels sent, or only some? Do those who are sent also remain in God's presence? Which orders are sent for which purposes?"
    },
    {
        "index": "112.1a",
        "refashioned": "Angels are sent by God on missions to the world. Being \"sent\" means being directed by a superior to carry out a task in a particular place or for a particular purpose. Since angels serve God and carry out His governance, God dispatches them to perform external ministrations -- guarding individuals, delivering messages, executing divine judgments.\n\nAngelic mission does not imply that the angel leaves God's presence. Angels remain always in the vision of God. Being sent means beginning a new operation in a particular place, not departing from the divine presence. The angel is simultaneously present to God and operationally active in the world."
    },
    {
        "index": "112.1b",
        "refashioned": "The internal act of an angel (contemplating God) and its external act (ministering in the world) are not in conflict. An angel can be fully in God's presence while performing an external task. The \"sending\" adds a new external operation; it does not interrupt the eternal internal one. This is partly why angels can be present everywhere they operate -- they are not limited by bodies that can only be in one place at a time."
    },
    {
        "index": "112.2",
        "refashioned": "Not all angels are sent on external missions. The highest orders -- Seraphim, Cherubim, and Thrones -- are not sent, because their function is entirely internal: direct contemplation and reception of divine illumination. The middle and lower orders handle external ministry.\n\nHowever, the highest angels can be said to \"send\" in the sense that they command and direct the missions of the lower angels. And in rare, extraordinary cases, even the highest angels might be involved in external operations -- but this would be exceptional and for the greatest purposes.\n\nThe principle at work is the same as in any well-structured organization: the highest levels set strategy and direction, while the lower levels execute on the ground. The CEO does not deliver packages, but the company's delivery operations ultimately reflect the CEO's direction."
    },
    {
        "index": "112.3",
        "refashioned": "The angels who are sent do still remain before God. Their external mission does not separate them from the divine presence. Every angel sent on a mission continues to see God, to contemplate divine truth, and to receive illumination. The mission is an additional activity, not a replacement for their contemplative union with God.\n\nThis resolves an apparent contradiction in Scripture, which describes some angels as always seeing the Father's face and other angels as being sent. The answer is that both descriptions apply to the same angels simultaneously. Being in God's presence and being operationally active in the world are not mutually exclusive for a spiritual being."
    },
    {
        "index": "112.4",
        "refashioned": "Different angelic orders handle different types of mission. The lowest order (Angels) handles ordinary individual ministry -- guarding persons, delivering routine messages. The next order (Archangels) handles missions of special importance -- major announcements, significant interventions. Principalities handle missions that concern nations or large groups.\n\nMoving higher into the middle hierarchy: Powers deal with matters that involve resisting evil forces. Virtues handle missions that involve extraordinary operations. Dominations direct but do not themselves execute external missions.\n\nThe general principle: the rank of the angel corresponds to the importance and scope of the mission. The greater the task, the higher the angel sent to accomplish it. The Annunciation to Mary was accomplished by an Archangel because it was a message of supreme importance concerning the salvation of all humanity."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.0",
        "refashioned": "We now turn specifically to the guardian angels -- the good angels assigned to protect and guide individual human beings. Eight questions: Are human beings guarded by angels? Is each person assigned one specific angel? Is guardianship only for some angels or also for the higher orders? Does every single person have a guardian angel? When does guardianship begin? Does the guardian angel ever leave? Does the guardian grieve over the person's sins? Can there be conflict among guardian angels?"
    },
    {
        "index": "113.1",
        "refashioned": "Human beings are guarded by angels. The reasoning follows from the general structure of divine governance established earlier: God governs lower things through higher things, physical through spiritual, less perfect through more perfect. Since human beings are imperfect creatures navigating a path toward an end that exceeds their natural powers (union with God), they need guidance from beings who see more clearly.\n\nGuardian angels function like guides on a difficult trail. The human being can walk, but the trail is dangerous and the destination is beyond what the traveler can see on their own. The guide provides direction, warns of hazards, and keeps the traveler oriented toward the goal."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.2",
        "refashioned": "Each individual person has one specific guardian angel assigned to them. The reason is not that one angel could not guard multiple people, but that the perfection of divine governance requires that individualized care. Since divine providence attends to every particular -- not just universals -- each person receives dedicated angelic attention.\n\nThis does not mean only one angel ever assists a given person. The guardian angel is the primary individual custodian, but other angels may also help in specific circumstances, particularly for tasks of greater importance. The personal guardian handles ordinary, ongoing protection; additional angelic assistance comes for extraordinary needs."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.3",
        "refashioned": "The guardianship of individuals belongs specifically to the lowest order of angels. The reason is structural: individual human care is the most particular form of ministry, and the lowest order handles the most particular tasks. Higher orders handle more universal governance -- nations, institutions, cosmic processes.\n\nBut the guardianship is not isolated work. The guardian angel of an individual operates within the broader system: it receives direction from higher orders, which in turn receive direction from still higher orders, up to God Himself. The individual guardian is the local agent of a universal governance system."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.4",
        "refashioned": "Every human being without exception has a guardian angel -- believers and unbelievers, saints and sinners. The guardianship is based on human nature and the general order of divine providence, not on the individual's merit or faith. As long as a person is alive and on the path toward their final end (whether they know it or not), they have an angel guarding them.\n\nEven Christ in His human nature had angelic ministry, not because He needed protection, but because the full ordering of divine governance applied to His human nature. The guardian angel's role is not just protection from harm but guidance toward the good -- and this applies to every person alive."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.5",
        "refashioned": "The guardian angel is assigned from the moment of birth. Some argue for assignment from the moment of conception, but the more fitting view ties guardianship to the human being's emergence into the world as an independent agent navigating external dangers and opportunities.\n\nBefore birth, the child is part of the mother and falls under her guardian's care. After birth, the child is a separate person requiring separate guardianship. The assignment is permanent -- the same angel guards the person from birth to death."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.6",
        "refashioned": "The guardian angel never entirely abandons its charge. Even when a person sins grievously, the angel does not withdraw. The angel may, in a certain sense, be said to \"leave\" when it does not prevent some evil from occurring -- but this is not abandonment. It reflects either divine permission (allowing the person to experience consequences) or the limits of angelic influence over free will.\n\nThe guardian's assignment is based on divine providence, not on the person's behavior. Just as a doctor does not stop treating a patient who ignores medical advice, the guardian angel continues its work regardless of the person's cooperation. The guardianship endures until death."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.7",
        "refashioned": "Guardian angels do not grieve in the way we understand grief. They are in a state of perfect beatitude, and the loss of one they guard does not diminish that beatitude. However, they can be said to grieve in an analogical sense: they desire the salvation of their charges and, when that salvation is frustrated by the person's free choices, their will is in a sense unfulfilled regarding that particular intention.\n\nBut this does not produce suffering. The angel wills the person's good but ultimately accepts the divine ordering that permits free creatures to reject their own good. The angel's joy in God is not contingent on the success or failure of any particular mission."
    },
    {
        "index": "113.8",
        "refashioned": "There is no genuine conflict among guardian angels. When the interests of different people seem to conflict, their respective guardian angels do not oppose one another, because all guardian angels operate under the same divine governance and aim at the same ultimate end.\n\nIf two people are in competition or conflict, their angels are both working toward the universal good, which may involve one person's temporal interests giving way to another's. The angels coordinate within the divine plan rather than acting as partisan advocates for their individual charges. Unlike human advocates in a legal dispute, guardian angels serve a common superior and a common purpose."
    },
    {
        "index": "114.0",
        "refashioned": "We now consider the attacks of demons on human beings. Five questions: Do demons assault humans? Is temptation proper to the devil? Can demons cause all human sins? Can they work real miracles to deceive? Is a demon who is defeated by a human restrained from further attacks?"
    },
    {
        "index": "114.1",
        "refashioned": "Demons do assault human beings, but not out of any correction-oriented purpose. While the good angels guard humans out of charity and in service to divine governance, demons attack out of envy and malice -- they desire to prevent humans from attaining the happiness they themselves have lost.\n\nGod permits these assaults not because He desires human suffering but because they serve the larger purpose of testing and strengthening human virtue. An athlete who trains only against weak opponents never develops full strength. The human moral life benefits from genuine opposition, even from a malicious source, because overcoming it builds real virtue.\n\nDemonic assault is therefore incorporated into divine governance, not as something God causes but as something He permits and turns toward good purpose."
    },
    {
        "index": "114.2",
        "refashioned": "Temptation in the sense of testing belongs properly to the devil's activity. A tempter probes for weaknesses to exploit them. The devil tempts by presenting apparent goods that are actually disordered, hoping to lead people into sin.\n\nBut the devil is not the cause of all temptation. Temptation also arises from human nature itself -- from disordered desires (what traditional theology calls concupiscence) and from the attractions of worldly goods. A person can be tempted by their own desires without any demonic involvement.\n\nThe devil's role is to add external pressure and cunning to the temptations that human nature already generates internally. He exploits existing vulnerabilities rather than creating them from scratch."
    },
    {
        "index": "114.3",
        "refashioned": "Not all sins are caused by demons. Demons can tempt, suggest, and present occasions for sin, but the human will remains the decisive factor. Many sins arise entirely from human free will and disordered desire without any demonic prompting.\n\nThe devil's influence is real but limited. He can present tempting scenarios, inflame passions through the imagination and bodily processes, and persistently pressure the will -- but he cannot force the will to consent. Even where demonic temptation is present, the sin belongs to the person who freely chooses it.\n\nSome theological traditions attributed every sin to direct demonic causation, but this overstates the case. Human beings are quite capable of sinning on their own initiative."
    },
    {
        "index": "114.4a",
        "refashioned": "Demons cannot perform true miracles. As established earlier, miracles in the strict sense exceed the entire order of created nature, and demons are part of that order. What demons can do is produce effects that seem miraculous to us -- effects that exceed human power and understanding but not the total power of created nature.\n\nDemons accomplish these seemingly miraculous effects by their superior knowledge of natural causes and their ability to manipulate physical forces with superhuman speed and precision. They know which natural substances produce which effects, they can move things instantaneously, and they can arrange conditions to produce outcomes that appear supernatural."
    },
    {
        "index": "114.4b",
        "refashioned": "There are three categories of demonic deception that mimic miracles. First, demons can manipulate physical matter to produce real but naturally explainable effects that astonish observers. Second, they can affect the imagination and senses to make people perceive things that are not actually happening -- illusions rather than real changes. Third, they can exploit natural processes that humans do not understand, producing effects whose natural causes are simply hidden from us.\n\nThe test for distinguishing true miracles from demonic counterfeits lies not primarily in the spectacle itself but in the purpose it serves and the authority behind it. True miracles serve the manifestation of divine truth and come with the marks of divine authority. Demonic wonders serve deception and disorder."
    },
    {
        "index": "114.5",
        "refashioned": "When a demon is resisted and overcome in temptation, it is restrained for a time from attacking the same person with the same temptation. This is a matter of divine governance, not of the demon's own choice -- the demon would happily return immediately, but God's providence imposes limits.\n\nThis restraint is not absolute or permanent. The demon may return later, or other demons may tempt the same person. But the principle stands that successful resistance to temptation earns a respite, both as a reward for the person's virtue and as a manifestation of divine ordering that keeps demonic assaults within manageable bounds."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.0",
        "refashioned": "We now examine how physical bodies themselves act as causes. This addresses a foundational question: do material things genuinely cause effects in other material things, or is all causation really divine? Six questions: Is any body capable of being an active cause? Are there hidden powers (seminal reasons) embedded in matter? Are heavenly bodies causes of what happens in the lower world? Can heavenly bodies cause human thought? Can demons use heavenly bodies for their purposes? Do heavenly bodies impose necessity on things under their influence?"
    },
    {
        "index": "115.1a",
        "refashioned": "Physical bodies are genuine active causes. The opposing view -- that bodies cannot truly act, that all apparent physical causation is really God acting directly -- proves too much. If bodies had no real causal power, the entire diversity of physical natures would be meaningless. Why would God create fire with the nature of fire if fire does not actually burn things?\n\nDenying real physical causation effectively denies that physical natures are real, which contradicts both observation and the principle that God creates things with genuine natures, not illusory ones."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.1b",
        "refashioned": "The argument for genuine physical causation runs deeper. Every being acts insofar as it is actual -- that is, insofar as it has real form and existence. Since physical things genuinely exist and have real forms (established in previous questions), they genuinely act. To deny a body's capacity to cause is to deny it real existence.\n\nTwo errors arise from denying physical causation. Some ancient philosophers denied that matter had any real forms, reducing all physical properties to arrangements of atoms. Others, like the Islamic occasionalists, held that all forms are directly impressed by God at every moment, with physical causes being mere occasions rather than real agents. Both positions fail because they deny what observation clearly shows: physical things act according to stable, natural powers that belong to them.\n\nThe truth: physical bodies act by their own forms and powers, which are real, though these powers ultimately derive from and depend on God as the first cause. Secondary causation is genuine causation."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.1c",
        "refashioned": "The objection that only spiritual beings can truly act -- because action requires transcending matter -- misunderstands the relationship between form and matter. A physical thing acts through its form, which, while inhering in matter, is not reducible to matter. The form gives the thing its active power. A fire heats because of its form (the active principle of heat), not because of its matter as such.\n\nSo physical action is real but limited: physical causes can only act on things that are disposed to receive their action. Fire heats what is capable of being heated. Physical causation always involves a recipient that is in potency to the effect in question."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.2a",
        "refashioned": "Are there hidden \"seminal reasons\" embedded in matter -- latent causal powers planted by God at creation that unfold over time? Augustine used this concept to explain how new things appear in the world without requiring either new creation or purely random generation.\n\nThe answer is yes, in a qualified sense. Matter contains real potentialities that can be activated by appropriate causes. These are not fully formed powers waiting to spring out but genuine dispositions in matter that, when the right conditions and agents are present, enable the production of new forms. God created matter with these potentialities from the beginning.\n\nThe concept helps explain the relationship between divine providence and natural development: God does not need to intervene miraculously every time something new appears. Instead, He created a world whose matter contains the built-in potential for development when acted upon by natural causes."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.2b",
        "refashioned": "These seminal reasons are not deterministic blueprints. Matter does not contain complete, pre-formed organisms waiting to emerge (as preformationism later claimed). Rather, matter has a real but passive capacity to receive various forms under the right conditions. The \"seeds\" are potentialities, not miniature actualities.\n\nThis means natural development is genuinely creative -- new forms really are produced by the interaction of active causes with receptive matter -- while also being providentially grounded, since the potentialities were established by God in the original creation."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.3a",
        "refashioned": "Heavenly bodies (the sun, moon, and stars in Aquinas's cosmology) genuinely influence events in the terrestrial world. They do this not by magic or occult sympathy but through real physical causation -- primarily through light, heat, and motion.\n\nThe heavenly bodies are the most universal physical causes, affecting the broadest range of terrestrial processes. Changes in season, weather, tides, and biological cycles all depend on celestial motions. This is observable physical causation, not astrology in the superstitious sense.\n\nHowever, this celestial influence has limits. Heavenly bodies act on matter through physical qualities, and their effects are determined by the disposition of the matter receiving their influence. The same sunlight that melts wax hardens clay. The celestial cause provides the active influence; the terrestrial matter determines the specific outcome."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.3b",
        "refashioned": "Heavenly bodies do not directly produce substantial forms (like creating a new species from nothing) by their own power. They can only bring pre-existing potentialities in matter to actualization. The generation of living things, for instance, requires both celestial influence and the right material conditions on earth.\n\nThe power of heavenly bodies is real but instrumental. They are the most powerful natural agents in the physical world, but they remain physical agents acting within the physical order, not spiritual or supernatural forces."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.4a",
        "refashioned": "Heavenly bodies cannot directly cause human intellectual activity or willing. The intellect and will are spiritual powers that operate without bodily organs (at least in their essential acts), and no physical cause -- however powerful -- can directly act on a spiritual power.\n\nHowever, heavenly bodies can influence human thought and decision indirectly, by affecting the body. Human thinking depends on imagination and sense experience, which depend on bodily organs, which are physical things subject to celestial influence. So the heavenly bodies can affect the bodily conditions (temperament, mood, physical disposition) that influence -- but do not determine -- intellectual and voluntary activity.\n\nThis is why astrological predictions about human behavior have a limited, statistical validity: celestial influences affect the bodily dispositions that incline people toward certain behaviors, and most people follow their inclinations without resistance. But any individual can override these inclinations through intellect and will, which is why astrology cannot predict the choices of a free, rational agent."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.4b",
        "refashioned": "The practical upshot: astrology can describe general tendencies in populations (since most people follow their passions, and passions are influenced by physical conditions) but cannot determine individual free choices. The wise person is \"the master of the stars\" -- not because the stars have no influence, but because reason and will can override whatever bodily inclinations the stars produce."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.5",
        "refashioned": "Demons do make use of celestial influences for their purposes. Since heavenly bodies produce real physical effects, and demons have superior knowledge of how these effects work, demons can time their temptations and manipulations to coincide with celestial conditions that make humans more susceptible.\n\nDemonic use of celestial power does not mean the heavenly bodies are evil or that celestial influence is inherently sinister. The bodies are natural causes operating as God designed them. Demons exploit them the way a criminal exploits any tool -- the tool is neutral; the intent is corrupt.\n\nThis also means that not every correlation between celestial events and unusual occurrences is demonic. Most are natural. Demons can exploit natural effects, but the natural effects would occur regardless."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.6a",
        "refashioned": "Heavenly bodies do not impose necessity on things subject to their influence. Their effects can be and often are impeded by other causes. Celestial influence interacts with the particular conditions of terrestrial matter, and those conditions can deflect, modify, or block the celestial effect.\n\nThis is true even for natural physical effects: the same solar heat that normally causes growth can cause destruction in drought conditions. The celestial cause is real but not irresistible. The more particular and contingent the terrestrial conditions, the less predictable the outcome of celestial influence.\n\nFor human beings, the case is even stronger. Since human intellect and will are not physical and not subject to physical causation, celestial bodies cannot impose any necessity on human choices. They can influence the body, which influences inclinations, but inclinations are not decisions. The human being retains the freedom to act against any natural inclination."
    },
    {
        "index": "115.6b",
        "refashioned": "This means that while celestial bodies are genuine physical causes with real effects on the material world, they are never sufficient causes of any particular terrestrial event (because other conditions always co-determine the outcome), and they are never causes at all of human free choices (because the will is not a physical power). The claim that \"the stars compel\" is false in both its strong form (physical necessity) and its application to human action."
    },
    {
        "index": "116.1a",
        "refashioned": "Does fate exist? Some Christian thinkers rejected the concept entirely, and others (like the Stoics) made fate an absolute cosmic necessity. The truth lies between these extremes.\n\nBoethius defines fate as \"a disposition inherent in changeable things, by which Providence connects each one with its proper order.\" This definition is workable if properly understood."
    },
    {
        "index": "116.1b",
        "refashioned": "Fate is real, but it is not what most people think it is. Events that seem random when viewed from the perspective of their immediate causes are often directly intended when viewed from a higher cause. Two strangers meeting by chance at a coffee shop might be there because a mutual friend separately suggested the same place to each -- the meeting is coincidence from their perspective but intended from the friend's.\n\nSome philosophers denied fate and providence entirely, attributing everything to uncoordinated chance. Others went to the opposite extreme, attributing every event to an inescapable cosmic mechanism -- the stars, material necessity, or an impersonal chain of causes.\n\nThe correct view: the ordering of secondary causes toward their effects, insofar as that ordering falls under divine providence, can be called fate. Fate is not a separate power competing with or operating independently of God. It is simply the name for how divine providence unfolds through the chain of created causes. When we speak of fate, we are speaking of providence as it appears from within the created order.\n\nUnderstood this way, fate is real but subordinate. God's providence is the plan; fate is its execution through secondary causes."
    },
    {
        "index": "116.2",
        "refashioned": "Fate is located in the secondary causes through which providence operates, not in God Himself. Providence is the eternal plan in the divine mind; fate is the unfolding of that plan through the network of created causes.\n\nThe distinction matters. If fate were identified with God's will directly, everything would happen by absolute necessity, since God's will cannot fail. But fate operates through created causes, which include contingent and free causes. So fate does not impose necessity on everything. The chain of secondary causes includes some that are necessary and some that are contingent, and the effects of each type correspond to the nature of its cause.\n\nTo confuse fate with divine will directly is to collapse the distinction between primary and secondary causation -- a mistake that would eliminate real contingency and real freedom from the world."
    },
    {
        "index": "116.3",
        "refashioned": "Fate is not unchangeable in the sense of absolute cosmic rigidity. Since fate operates through secondary causes, and secondary causes can be impeded or redirected (by other secondary causes or by divine intervention), the particular outcomes that fate tends toward are not fixed with iron necessity.\n\nFate is changeable in two senses. First, the secondary causes through which it operates can be modified -- a natural cause can be overridden by a stronger cause, including free human choice. Second, God can act outside the order of secondary causes entirely (miracles), which interrupts what the chain of natural causes would otherwise produce.\n\nWhat is unchangeable is not fate but providence: the eternal plan in God's mind. Providence encompasses both the natural order (fate) and any exceptions to it. Fate is the regular pattern; providence is the complete plan."
    },
    {
        "index": "116.4",
        "refashioned": "Not everything is subject to fate. Fate, properly understood, is the ordering of secondary causes. But some things are directly effected by God without secondary causes -- creation from nothing, the infusion of grace, the beatific vision. These fall under providence but not under fate, since fate only covers what happens through the chain of created causes.\n\nAlso, human free will is subject to providence but not to fate in any deterministic sense. Free choices are part of the providential order (God foresees and incorporates them) but are not caused by the chain of physical secondary causes that constitutes fate. The will operates above the physical causal chain.\n\nSo the scope of fate is narrower than the scope of providence. Everything under fate is under providence, but not everything under providence is under fate. This distinction preserves both the reality of natural order and the reality of freedom and grace."
    },
    {
        "index": "117.0",
        "refashioned": "We now examine how human beings act on one another and on the world around them. Four questions: Can one person teach another in the sense of causing knowledge? Can human beings teach angels? Can a human being change physical matter by the power of the soul alone? Can the separated soul (after death) move physical bodies?"
    },
    {
        "index": "117.1a",
        "refashioned": "Can one person cause knowledge in another -- is teaching real? The question is whether the teacher is a genuine cause of the student's knowledge or merely provides external stimulation while knowledge arises entirely from within the student.\n\nTwo extreme positions fail. Plato's view that learning is merely remembering innate knowledge makes the teacher irrelevant. The opposite view that the teacher implants knowledge directly into a purely passive student ignores the active role of the learner's intellect."
    },
    {
        "index": "117.1b",
        "refashioned": "Teaching is a genuine form of causation, but it works by activating what is already potentially present in the student, not by transferring knowledge like pouring water into a glass.\n\nThe student's intellect is not a blank slate -- it possesses the first principles of reason (basic logical axioms, the principle of non-contradiction, etc.) as natural endowments. All further knowledge is potentially derivable from these principles. The teacher's role is to guide the student's intellect from what it already knows (principles) to what it does not yet know (conclusions), by presenting the right middle terms, examples, and sensory illustrations.\n\nThis is real causation: the teacher is the agent that moves the student from potential knowledge to actual knowledge. But it is instrumental causation, working through and with the student's own intellectual activity, not bypassing it. The student must actively process, abstract, and reason from what the teacher provides. Teaching fails when the student's intellect is not engaged.\n\nThe analogy to physical causation: a doctor does not create health from nothing but works with the body's own healing powers, applying external remedies that activate the body's natural tendency toward health. Similarly, the teacher applies external instruction that activates the mind's natural tendency toward knowledge."
    },
    {
        "index": "117.1c",
        "refashioned": "So knowledge can be acquired in two ways: by discovery (the intellect working on its own from principles to conclusions) and by instruction (the intellect working with external help from a teacher). In both cases, the same intellectual process occurs -- reasoning from known principles to new conclusions. The teacher simply supplies what the individual discoverer would have to supply for themselves: the intermediate steps, the examples, the sensory illustrations that make abstract truths graspable."
    },
    {
        "index": "117.2",
        "refashioned": "Human beings cannot teach angels in the proper sense. Angels grasp truths through direct intellectual intuition, not through the step-by-step reasoning from sensory experience that humans use. Since teaching works by presenting sensory examples and middle terms to guide a discursive intellect, and angels do not reason discursively, the human mode of teaching has no purchase on the angelic mode of knowing.\n\nHowever, angels can learn something from human beings in a limited sense: they can come to know the free choices and interior thoughts of humans, which are hidden from angelic perception until the person reveals them through action or speech. This is not teaching (since it involves no intellectual illumination) but disclosure -- the angel learns a particular fact rather than gaining understanding of a truth."
    },
    {
        "index": "117.3",
        "refashioned": "The human soul cannot directly alter physical matter by thought alone. The soul's direct causal power over matter extends only to its own body, and even there, only through the established biological mechanisms. The soul moves its body through the intermediary of bodily organs and processes; it does not reshape matter by pure willing.\n\nSome souls, in special states (such as intense emotional agitation), can produce bodily effects that extend beyond the normal range -- the so-called \"evil eye\" in folk traditions reflects a real observation that intense psychological states can produce physiological effects that affect others nearby. But this works through physical causation (bodily emanations, changes in the person's physical state), not through direct soul-to-matter action.\n\nClaims that the soul can directly transform external matter -- turning lead into gold, moving objects by thought -- are false if understood as the soul's own natural power. If such effects occur, they are produced either through physical means the person is unaware of, or through the intervention of spiritual agents (angels or demons)."
    },
    {
        "index": "117.4",
        "refashioned": "Can the separated soul (the soul after death, apart from the body) move physical things? By its natural power alone, no. The separated soul lacks the bodily instruments through which it normally acts on the physical world.\n\nHowever, the separated soul can move bodies by power received from God or by the assistance of spiritual beings. In cases where the dead appear to affect the physical world, this occurs either through divine permission and power or through angelic (or demonic) mediation -- not through the soul's own natural capacity.\n\nThe key principle: the soul's natural relationship to matter is mediated through its own body. Once separated from the body, it has no natural capacity to act on physical things unless empowered from above."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.0",
        "refashioned": "We now consider the origin of the human soul. Three questions: Is the soul transmitted by biological generation (like the body)? Is the soul produced from pre-existing spiritual matter? Or is the soul directly created by God for each new human being?"
    },
    {
        "index": "118.1a",
        "refashioned": "Is the human soul generated through biological reproduction -- transmitted from parent to child the way the body is? Some thinkers held that it was, reasoning that since the soul is the form of the body, and forms are normally produced when matter is prepared to receive them, the soul should arise naturally from the biological process.\n\nThis view faces serious difficulties. The human soul, as established earlier, is intellectual and subsistent -- it operates beyond matter and can exist independently of the body. No purely material process can produce an immaterial, subsistent entity."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.1b",
        "refashioned": "The soul cannot be generated biologically. Biological generation works by transmitting form through matter -- the parents' biological material shapes the offspring's biological material. But the intellectual soul transcends matter. Its essential operation -- understanding -- does not depend on any bodily organ. An immaterial power cannot be produced by a material process.\n\nThe attempt to save this position by saying the soul is \"virtually\" contained in the parents' reproductive power fails. A cause cannot produce an effect that exceeds its own nature. Material causes can produce material effects; only a spiritual cause can produce a spiritual effect."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.1c",
        "refashioned": "This means the old theory of \"traducianism\" -- that the soul is transmitted through biological reproduction like a cutting from a plant -- is incorrect. The human intellectual soul cannot be split off from the parents' souls or generated from biological material. If the soul were material enough to be biologically transmitted, it would be too material to perform intellectual operations. If it is immaterial enough to understand, it is too immaterial to be biologically generated.\n\nThe sensitive and vegetative functions of the soul are initially generated biologically in the embryo, but the intellectual soul that supersedes them must come from outside the biological process."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.2a",
        "refashioned": "Is the soul produced from pre-existing spiritual matter, the way physical things are produced from physical matter? No. The soul has no matter as part of its essence. It is a purely immaterial form.\n\nThe suggestion that there might be a spiritual \"matter\" from which souls are made misunderstands what matter is. Matter is potentiality to receive form, and it is the principle of individuation in physical things. The soul is individuated not by matter but by its relationship to the particular body it informs. And the soul's immateriality -- its capacity for intellectual operations that transcend any physical organ -- rules out its being composed of anything material or quasi-material."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.2b",
        "refashioned": "Some thinkers proposed that God created all souls at the beginning and stores them until they are joined to bodies. Others proposed that souls pre-exist in some spiritual realm and descend into bodies. Both positions are rejected.\n\nIf souls pre-existed, they would have had prior experiences and knowledge, which we do not observe in newborns. The union of soul and body is natural, not a punishment or accident, so the soul should not exist naturally without a body. And the idea that God created all souls at once contradicts the ongoing generation of new human beings.\n\nThe correct position, which follows from rejecting both biological generation and pre-existence of souls, is that each human soul is directly created by God at the moment the body is sufficiently prepared to receive it. The soul comes into being through divine creation, not through any natural process."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.3a",
        "refashioned": "Each human soul is individually and directly created by God. This is the only position consistent with the soul's nature. Since the soul is immaterial and subsistent, it cannot be produced by any material cause (ruling out biological generation). Since it has no matter, it cannot be formed from pre-existing material (ruling out production from spiritual matter). Since it exists naturally in union with a body, it should not pre-exist that body.\n\nTherefore: God creates each soul at the moment the body is ready for it. This is not a production from nothing in the temporal sense of a dramatic intervention; it is the natural order of things that, for this type of entity, coming-to-be means being created directly by God. Just as only God can create from nothing (because creation exceeds any secondary cause's power), only God can produce an intellectual soul.\n\nThe biological process of generation prepares the matter. God completes the process by creating the intellectual soul. Nature and divine action cooperate, each doing what belongs to its proper sphere."
    },
    {
        "index": "118.3b",
        "refashioned": "This raises an apparent difficulty: if God creates each soul, does He create souls of sinners, thereby being implicated in sin? No. God creates each soul good. Sin arises from the free will of the person, not from any defect in the soul's creation. Creating a being with free will means creating a being that can choose wrongly, but the possibility of sin is a consequence of freedom, not a product of divine causation."
    },
    {
        "index": "119.0",
        "refashioned": "Finally, we consider the propagation of the human body. Two questions: Is any part of our food converted into the reality of human nature? Is the human body's matter entirely derived from the parents, or does food genuinely become part of our substance?"
    },
    {
        "index": "119.1a",
        "refashioned": "Does food genuinely become part of the human body's substance, or does it merely pass through? Some ancient thinkers held that food only restores what is lost and does not become part of the body's essential nature. Others held that the body's original matter from conception remains forever, with food serving only as fuel.\n\nThe correct view is that food genuinely becomes part of the body's substance."
    },
    {
        "index": "119.1b",
        "refashioned": "Food truly becomes part of human bodily nature. The reasoning: the human body grows -- an infant's body is genuinely larger and contains more matter than it did at birth. This additional matter must come from somewhere, and it comes from food. If food did not truly become part of the body's substance, growth would be impossible.\n\nThe process works through the body's natural power of nutrition, which transforms food into the body's own substance. This is genuine substantial change, not mere addition. The bread you eat does not remain bread sitting inside you; it is converted into flesh, blood, and bone by the nutritive power.\n\nThe objection that the body's \"original\" matter (from the parents at conception) is the only true human matter, with food being a secondary or inferior addition, fails. If only the original parental matter counted as truly human, the body could never genuinely grow, and every cell not derived directly from the original conception would be foreign to the person. This is absurd. The body is constantly turning over its material while maintaining its identity through its form -- the soul.\n\nThe soul as the form of the body is what makes matter human, not the matter's origin. Whatever matter the soul informs and organizes as part of its body is genuinely human matter, regardless of whether it entered the body through conception or through Tuesday's lunch."
    },
    {
        "index": "119.1c",
        "refashioned": "This raises questions about bodily identity. If the body's matter is constantly being replaced through nutrition, what makes it the same body over time? The answer is the form -- the soul -- which persists through material change and maintains the body's organizational identity.\n\nThis is not unique to living things. A river remains the same river even though its water is constantly being replaced. The identity lies in the form and structure, not in the particular matter at any given moment. In the case of a human being, the soul is the principle of identity that makes the body one continuous thing despite constant material turnover.\n\nSo both things are true: food genuinely becomes part of the body's substance, and the body maintains its identity through time. The soul accounts for both truths simultaneously."
    },
    {
        "index": "119.2a",
        "refashioned": "Is the matter for a new human being's body entirely derived from the parents, or can food and other external material become part of the essential human substance transmitted in generation?\n\nThe reproductive material (semen, in Aquinas's biology) is derived from the surplus of the parents' nutritive process -- it is food that has been fully converted into the parents' bodily substance and then separated for the purpose of generation. So in one sense, everything in the new body traces back to food that became part of the parents' substance.\n\nBut the key point is that what is transmitted is not just matter but an active formative power. The parents' reproductive material does not contain a miniature human being; it contains an active power that directs the development of new matter into a human body. This formative power organizes whatever suitable matter is available -- first the maternal material, then (after birth) food.\n\nThe parents provide the initial matter and the active formative power. The food consumed after birth continues the process of building and maintaining the body. The soul, when created by God and united to the body, takes over as the ultimate principle of the body's organization and identity."
    },
    {
        "index": "119.2b",
        "refashioned": "The formative power in the parents' reproductive material is not the intellectual soul itself (which is created by God, not transmitted biologically). It is a natural, biological power that directs embryonic development. This power prepares the matter for the reception of the soul but does not produce the soul.\n\nOnce the soul is present, it is the soul that governs all further bodily development, nutrition, and growth. The formative power of the reproductive material has done its work -- it prepared a body suitable for receiving a human soul. From that point forward, the soul is the body's form, and all material that enters the body through nutrition becomes part of that soul-informed substance.\n\nThis account preserves the roles of both nature and divine action in human generation: nature provides the material and the biological formative power; God provides the intellectual soul; and the result is a complete human being, body and soul."
    }
]

